{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e9a53b6-61c7-4c79-8003-d41e384234dd","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to use **`System.IO.Abstractions`**:\n\n1. **Install** the NuGet package `System.IO.Abstractions`\n2. **Replace** direct `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls with `IFileSystem` (injected via DI):\n   ```csharp\n   public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)\n   {\n       public string Load(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);\n       public void Save(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n       public bool DirExists(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);\n   }\n   ```\n3. **Register** in DI: `services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem>(new FileSystem());`\n4. **In tests**, use `MockFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:\n   ```csharp\n   var fs = new MockFileSystem();\n   fs.AddFile(\"/data.txt\", new MockFileData(\"hello\"));\n   var svc = new MyService(fs);\n   Assert.Equal(\"hello\", svc.Load(\"/data.txt\"));\n   ```\n\nThis gives you a drop-in `IFileSystem` abstraction with an in-memory mock — no custom interfaces needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e28c7099-e740-46af-8d98-9d4bfc8b949d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a general software engineering question about best practices, not a task requiring code changes. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"4C46:1BD058:DA1247:10AB7E6:6A0136AA"},"id":"369de792-8e5f-4a0d-a68d-e44a8fbbc04c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:53:54.452Z","parentId":"fb925a06-1e12-43bb-b65e-6b44253cd8e3"}
